   <reviews>
      <review>
         <snippet>This horror comedy is loaded with decapitations, bodies torn in two and spewing blood, and yet, unlike the grim, torture-filled gore-fests of late, Hatchet’s mayhem is so giddily over-the-top that you end up applauding the low-budget aplomb of it all.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film-reviews/film-reviews-310-to-yuma-exiled-hatchet/17173/?page=2</url>
         <critic>Chuck Wilson</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>No other film in recent memory has featured such a terrifically retro maniac or revisited the heyday of Eighties gore films with such gleeful, moist abandon.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid%3A531001</url>
         <critic>Marc Savlov</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>This is not a film intended for a wide audience. But B-movie fans who find their way to Adam Green's gory schlock extravaganza are going to like it.</snippet>
         <url>http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-070907-movies-review-hatchet,0,4979873.story?coll=mmx-movies_top_heds</url>
         <critic>Scott Schueller</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Hatchet is further evidence of the decline of Western civilization.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070907.whatchet07/BNStory/Entertainment/home</url>
         <critic>Stephen Cole</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Director Adam Green's genuine affection for the genre helps make Hatchet a cut above average.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.nypost.com/seven/09072007/entertainment/movies/a_cut_above_usual_slash.htm</url>
         <critic>Lou Lumenick</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Horror without suspense is like sex without love: you can appreciate the technicalities, but ultimately there’s no reason to care.</snippet>
         <url>http://movies.nytimes.com/2007/09/07/movies/07hatc.html?ref=movies</url>
         <critic>Jeannette Catsoulis</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Joel David Moore leads a cast full of token minorities and bickering bimbos, whom writer-helmer Adam Green dispatches with knowing glee and an obvious love for genre conventions that almost overcomes the derivative scripting.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117934668.html?categoryid=31&amp;cs=1</url>
         <critic>Justin Chang</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Even after appropriately lowering expectations, it's kind to call this one a cut below.</snippet>
